From 8047a1de15639939942cc387dc8adc36f489cf11 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Nadia Yvette Chambers <nadia.yvette.chambers@ik.me>
Date: Wed, 17 Jun 2026 12:44:14 +0200
Subject: [PATCH 155/174] x86/mm: PGCL: free the MMUPAGE-granular ioremap
 memtype range in iounmap

__ioremap_caller() reserves the PAT memtype over an MMUPAGE-granular
range:

    phys_addr &= MMUPAGE_MASK;
    size = ALIGN(last_addr + 1, MMUPAGE_SIZE) - phys_addr;
    memtype_reserve(phys_addr, phys_addr + size, ...);

This is deliberate (see the comment there): the hardware page is
MMUPAGE_SIZE, and rounding the reservation up to the cluster PAGE_SIZE
would over-claim into adjacent MMIO BARs / RAM and either spuriously
fail memtype_reserve() or collide with a neighbour's reservation.

iounmap() freed the memtype over get_vm_area_size() instead:

    memtype_free(p->phys_addr, p->phys_addr + get_vm_area_size(p));

get_vm_area_size() returns the vm_area span, which __get_vm_area_node()
rounded UP to PAGE_SIZE (the cluster).  Under PGCL (PAGE_SIZE >
MMUPAGE_SIZE) that end exceeds the reserved end for any MMIO region that
is not a whole cluster.  memtype_erase() requires an EXACT [start,end]
match (arch/x86/mm/pat/memtype_interval.c), so the oversized free
returns -EINVAL:

    x86/PAT: <comm>:<pid> freeing invalid memtype [mem ...]

and the struct memtype rbtree node is leaked.  On real hardware this is
a storm: every iounmap() of a sub-cluster BAR (GPU/PCI MMIO around
0xfd6xxxxx) warns, and over earlycon=efifb the flood inflates boot by
many minutes and trips the soft-lockup detector.

Free the exact range that was reserved by using area->requested_size --
the unrounded size that __get_vm_area_node() records before its internal
ALIGN() (mm/vmalloc.c).  p->phys_addr already holds the MMUPAGE-aligned
start, so [p->phys_addr, p->phys_addr + p->requested_size] is byte-for-
byte the range memtype_reserve() inserted.

Newton (PAGE_MMUSHIFT==0): MMUPAGE_SIZE == PAGE_SIZE, so size is already
PAGE-aligned and requested_size == get_vm_area_size(); the change is a
behavioural no-op at shift 0 and reproduces mainline exactly.

memtype.c / memtype_interval.c are unmodified by PGCL; the defect was
purely the unit mismatch on the iounmap side of this caller.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 <noreply@anthropic.com>
---
 arch/x86/mm/ioremap.c | 13 ++++++++++++-
 1 file changed, 12 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/arch/x86/mm/ioremap.c b/arch/x86/mm/ioremap.c
index 9cadcefd1c2c..4196604ed21f 100644
--- a/arch/x86/mm/ioremap.c
+++ b/arch/x86/mm/ioremap.c
@@ -497,7 +497,18 @@ void iounmap(volatile void __iomem *addr)
 
 	kmsan_iounmap_page_range((unsigned long)addr,
 		(unsigned long)addr + get_vm_area_size(p));
-	memtype_free(p->phys_addr, p->phys_addr + get_vm_area_size(p));
+	/*
+	 * Free the exact memtype range that __ioremap_caller() reserved, which
+	 * is MMUPAGE-granular (area->requested_size, the unrounded size passed
+	 * to get_vm_area_caller()).  Do NOT use get_vm_area_size(): under PGCL
+	 * (PAGE_SIZE > MMUPAGE_SIZE) it rounds the span up to the cluster
+	 * PAGE_SIZE, so it would hand memtype_free() a larger end than was
+	 * reserved.  memtype_erase() requires an exact [start,end] match, so the
+	 * oversized free fails ("freeing invalid memtype") and leaks the memtype
+	 * rbtree node.  Identity at PAGE_MMUSHIFT==0, where requested_size and
+	 * get_vm_area_size() coincide (size is already PAGE/MMUPAGE-aligned).
+	 */
+	memtype_free(p->phys_addr, p->phys_addr + p->requested_size);
 
 	/* Finally remove it */
 	o = remove_vm_area((void __force *)addr);
